2020 Presidential Election - Twitter Sentiment Analysis¶

IST 736 - Final Project

  • Thomas Marianos

Introduction¶

The 2020 U.S. election was not the first in the social media age, but it did seem to spark more debate over social media tools and their role in influencing elections. Scrutiny over the candidates' use of Twitter as well as an investigation into Russian bot accounts used to spread misinformation dominated the news cycle for months. This analysis will take a look at Tweets with the hashtags #DonaldTrump and #JoeBiden to see if there was any indication of general sentiment supporting one or the other, as well as if we can predict the sentiment of a Tweet depending on who it is directed to.

The dataset used for this analysis is a Twitter Scrape found on Kaggle containing the tweet itself, the twitter handle, and other metadata about the tweet.

  • created_at: Date and time of tweet creation
  • tweet_id: Unique ID of the tweet
  • tweet: Full tweet text
  • likes: Number of likes
  • retweet_count: Number of retweets
  • source: Utility used to post tweet
  • user_id: User ID of tweet creator
  • user_name: Username of tweet creator
  • user_screen_name: Screen name of tweet creator
  • user_description: Description of self by tweet creator
  • user_join_date: Join date of tweet creator
  • user_followers_count: Followers count on tweet creator
  • user_location: Location given on tweet creator's profile
  • lat: Latitude parsed from user_location
  • long: Longitude parsed from user_location
  • city: City parsed from user_location
  • country: Country parsed from user_location
  • state: State parsed from user_location
  • state_code: State code parsed from user_location
  • collected_at: Date and time tweet data was mined from twitter*

With this dataset, we will develop and implement a Vader Sentiment analysis to find the overall sentiment behind each tweet and then compare a Multinomial Naive Bayes model against a Support Vector Machine model and see which performs best when predicting the sentiment.

tweets_df['tweet']=tweets_df['tweet'].str.lower()
# # Proprocessing the data
#Code to remove the Hashtags from the text
tweets_df['tweet']=tweets_df['tweet'].apply(lambda x:re.sub(r'\B#\S+','',str(x)))
# Code to remove the links from the text
tweets_df['tweet']=tweets_df['tweet'].apply(lambda x:re.sub(r"http\S+", "", x))
# Code to remove the Special characters from the text 
tweets_df['tweet']=tweets_df['tweet'].apply(lambda x:' '.join(re.findall(r'\w+', x)))
# Code to substitute the multiple spaces with single spaces
tweets_df['tweet']=tweets_df['tweet'].apply(lambda x:re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', x, flags=re.I))
# Code to remove all the single characters in the text
tweets_df['tweet']=tweets_df['tweet'].apply(lambda x:re.sub(r'\s+[a-zA-Z]\s+', '', x))
# Remove the twitter handlers
tweets_df['tweet']=tweets_df['tweet'].apply(lambda x:re.sub('@[^\s]+','',x))

Define functions to calculate tweet statistics

In [26]:
def corpus_stats(documents):
    """Function to print tweet-level and corpus-level statistics
    These include
    - Average number of characters per tweet
    - Average number of words per tweet
    - Average vocabulary size per tweet
    - Average lexical richness per tweet
    - Total number of words
    - Total vocabulary size
    - Total lexical richness
    - Average number of characters per word
    
    Arguments:
        documents {[list]} -- [list of strings i.e. tweets]
    """
    docs = [word_tokenize(tweet) for tweet in documents]    
    # tweet statistics
    print("observation level statistics:\n")
    # average number of characters per tweet
    avg_chars = int(sum([len(tweet) for tweet in documents]) / len(documents))
    print("Average number of characters per tweet: {:d}".format(avg_chars))
    # average number of words per tweet
    avg_words = int(sum([len(doc) for doc in docs]) / len(docs))
    print("Average number of words per tweet: {:d}".format(avg_words))
    # average vocabulary size per tweet
    avg_vocab = int(sum([len(set(doc)) for doc in docs]) / len(docs))
    print("Average vocabulary size per tweet: {:d}".format(avg_vocab))
    # average lexical richness per tweet (proportion of unique words to total words)
    avg_lex_rich = sum([len(set(doc))/len(doc) for doc in docs if len(doc) > 0]) / len(docs)
    print("Average lexical richness per tweet: {:.2f}".format(avg_lex_rich))
    # corpus statistics
    print("\nCorpus level statistics:\n")
    words = []
    for doc in docs:
        words.extend(doc)
    # total number of words
    print("Total number of words: {:d}".format(len(words)))
    # vocabulary size
    print("Total vocabulary size: {:d}".format(len(set(words))))
    # lexical richness
    print("Total lexical richness: {:.2f}".format(len(set(words)) / len(words)))
    # average number of characters per word
    word_lengths = [len(w) for w in words]
    print("Average number of characters per word: {:.2f}".format(sum(word_lengths) / len(word_lengths))) 

def term_freq(documents):
    """Function to plot top 50 common terms    
    
    Arguments:
        documents {[list]} -- [list of strings i.e. tweets]
    """
    docs = [word_tokenize(tweet) for tweet in documents]        
    words = []
    for doc in docs:
        words.extend(doc)
    filtered_words = [w for w in words if w.isalpha() if not w in stop_words]
    fdist = FreqDist(filtered_words)
    fdist = FreqDist(filtered_words)
    fdist.plot(50, title = 'Top 50 Most Common Words')

from wordcloud import WordCloud 

def get_wc(documents):
    """Function to plot word cloud
    
    Arguments:
        documents {[list]} -- [list of strings i.e. tweets]
    """ 
    docs = [word_tokenize(tweet) for tweet in documents]        
    words = []
    for doc in docs:
        words.extend(doc)
    filtered_words = [w for w in words if w.isalpha() if not w in stop_words]
    text = ' '.join(word for word in filtered_words)
    wordcloud = WordCloud(max_font_size=160,relative_scaling=1,background_color='white',colormap='GnBu',width=1000,height=700).generate(text)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

Sentiment Analysis¶

In [30]:
data = tweets_df[['tweet']]
In [31]:
# Copying the data into a new dataframe called vader
vader = data.copy()
sentiment = vad()

# Making additional columns for sentiment score in the vader dataframe
sen = ['Positive', 'Negative', 'Neutral']
sentiments = [sentiment.polarity_scores(i) for i in vader['tweet'].values]
vader['Negative Score'] = [i['neg'] for i in sentiments]
vader['Positive Score'] = [i['pos'] for i in sentiments]
vader['Neutral Score'] = [i['neu'] for i in sentiments]
vader['Compound Score'] = [i['compound'] for i in sentiments]
score = vader['Compound Score'].values

t = []
for i in score:
    if i >= 0.05 :
        t.append('Positive')
    elif i<= -0.05 :
        t.append('Negative')
    else:
        t.append('Neutral')
vader['OverallSentiment'] = t

Conclusion¶

In this analysis we first took a look at the data itself and found that, within the United States, there were more tweets with #JoeBiden in general, but #DonaldTrump was tweeted more often often in all of the top 10 states except Florida and Texas. Investigating the words within each group of tweets, we created some word clouds and found that there was a lot of overlap in the terms used for each, but with some standout differences such as the Trump tweets including keywords such as 'Deep State' and Biden tweets containing a lot of Hunter Biden references. We converted the tweets to a corpus and disected it for more details, finding that while #JoeBiden was tweeted more, the word 'trump' was the most frequent word within the dataset.

Now that we had a general overview of the dataset and the information contained, we moved forward and used the Vader Sentiment Analysis tool to find out the emotional sentiment behind each tweet by focusing on the polarity measures of the word choices. The vader tool showed that overall, most of the tweets analyzed seemed to be more neutral in tone, but those that did have a positive or negative sentiment more often included #DonaldTrump.

We split our data into 70% training data and 30% testing data and went forward with defining our Multinomial Naive Bayes model and our Support Vector Machine model. Implementing the models on our data, we found that the SVM algorithm out performed the MNB algorith predictions in all senses. The SVM accurracy score and cross validation scores were roughly 7% higher than the MNB and the precision, recall, and F1-scores showed that the SVM model was more precise, had less false negatives, and a stronger balance between the two measures.
